<TITLE> Clinton on talking to the Taliban </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 London, Jan 29 (bdnews24.com/Reuters)--- US Secretary of state Hillary Clinton says the road to peace in Afghanistan may include talking to the Taliban. Talking to your enemies. US Secretary of State Hillary Clinton said in order to bring peace to Afghanistan, it may mean talking to the Taliban and other insurgent forces. SOUNDBITE: U.S. Secretary of State Hillary Clinton, saying (English): "I think the starting premise is you don't make peace with your friends. You have to be willing to engage with your enemies if you expect to create a situation that ends an insurgency or so marginalizes the remaining insurgents that it doesn't pose a threat to the stability and security of the people." Clinton's comments came at a new conference following a London meeting on Afghanistan. Earlier Afghan President Hamid Karzai told the conference that he wanted Saudi Arabia -- a trusted go-between with the Taliban leadership -- to help bring peace. SOUNDBITE: U.S. Secretary of State Hillary Clinton, saying (English): "We have a very clear understanding of what we expect from this process. We expect that a lot of the foot soldiers on the battle field will be leaving the Taliban because a many of them have wanted to leave, many of them are tired of fighting. We believe the tide is beginning to turn against them and we need incentives in order to both protect them and provide alternatives to them to replace the payment they received as Taliban fighters." The comments come as the U.S. is sending in 30,000 more troops to Afghanistan to weaken the insurgency and convince the Taliban to accept a peace deal, which would require them to sever ties with al Qa
